+\begin{remark}[Branch convention for the Riemann--Siegel phase]
+\label{rem:theta-branch-convention}
+The branch \(L\) in Definition~\ref{def:riemann-siegel-phase} is the
+holomorphic logarithm of \(\Gamma\) on the half-plane \(\Re z>0\), not the
+principal logarithm applied pointwise to \(\Gamma(z)\).  This branch exists
+because \(\Gamma\) has no zeros or poles on \(\Re z>0\), and the half-plane
+is simply connected; the normalization on \((0,\infty)\) fixes the additive
+constant.  Any other holomorphic logarithm on a connected subdomain would
+change \(\theta\) only by an additive constant \(2\pi k\), which leaves
+\(q=\theta'\), the phase differences \(\theta(x)-\theta(y)\), and therefore
+\(K_\theta\) unchanged.  A discontinuous branch, such as a principal-branch
+representative with jumps, is not part of the definition and cannot be used
+for derivative identities.
+\end{remark}
